-- Stocks in South Africa Gain For Second Day, Altech and Impala Make Moves
-- B y   M i k e   C o h e n   a n d   F r a n z   W i l d
-- 2010-09-28T17:23:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-28/south-african-equities-bhp-billiton-anglo-american-cadiz.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  gained for the second successive day, rising 13.05,
or 0.1 percent, to 28,972.47 when it closed at 5:00 p.m. in
Johannesburg. The following were among the most active stocks in
the South African market today.       Allied Technologies Ltd.  (ALT SJ) retreated 70 cents, or
1.2 percent, to 57 rand. The electronics and telecommunications
holding company said first-half earnings fell to 202 million
rand ($29 million) in the six months through August, from 284
million rand a year earlier.  Amalgamated Electronic Corp.  (AER SJ), gained 8 cents, or
5.7 percent, to 1.49 rand, its biggest jump since Sept. 8. The
electronic security systems manufacturer said it had 2.8 million
rand in cash and cash equivalent by the end of the year through
March 31.  Cadiz Holdings Ltd.  (CDZ SJ) declined the most in almost
six months, slumping 15 cents, or 4.4 percent, to 3.25 rand. The
financial services holding company said per-share earnings in
the six months through September are expected to be at least 20
percent lower than a year earlier.  Famous Brands Ltd.  (FBR SJ) gained 1.29 rand, or 3.4
percent, to 39.29 rand, the most in more than three weeks. The
food and beverage company bought a 51 percent stake in Vovo Telo
Artisan Bakery.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest
producer of the metal, fell 2.57 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 176
rand, a second day of declines. Platinum for immediate delivery
shed as much as 1.7 percent to $1,604.50 an ounce.  Lonmin Plc  (LON SJ) fell 3.22 rand, or 1.7 percent, to
185.28 rand. The platinum miner was cut to ‘hold’ from ‘buy’ at
Liberum Capital.  To contact the reporters on this story:
